01:01:01.280 --> 01:01:03.620
One of the ones you might want
to know most about is the

01:01:03.620 --> 01:01:05.480
changing your initial
hunch answer.

01:01:05.480 --> 01:01:06.630
How do you know that?

01:01:06.630 --> 01:01:08.720
So the people have gone back
over test scores and looked

01:01:08.720 --> 01:01:11.180
where people crossed out an
answer or erased an answer.

01:01:11.180 --> 01:01:12.330
That's the best source
of evidence they

01:01:12.330 --> 01:01:13.530
have in large samples.

01:01:13.530 --> 01:01:17.260
And people are twice as likely
to give a better, the correct

01:01:17.260 --> 01:01:19.300
answer, than to move
to a wrong answer.

01:01:19.300 --> 01:01:21.870
That's the empirical evidence.

01:01:21.870 --> 01:01:25.830
So it's a fantastically
interesting disconnect that

01:01:25.830 --> 01:01:27.310
you see so many places.

01:01:27.310 --> 01:01:30.210
In teachers' advice, you go
with your first hunch when

01:01:30.210 --> 01:01:31.300
you're unsure.

01:01:31.300 --> 01:01:34.570
The empirical evidence is you're
much more likely to be

01:01:34.570 --> 01:01:38.550
