So the outcome was your grades
in medical school and your

01:05:45.610 --> 01:05:47.330
likelihood of completing
medical school.

01:05:47.330 --> 01:05:51.682
What else could an interview
have been relevant for?

01:05:51.682 --> 01:05:55.930
Maybe, maybe, maybe something
about bedside manner or how

01:05:55.930 --> 01:05:58.700
you relate to people, maybe,
maybe, maybe, but there's no

01:05:58.700 --> 01:06:00.070
evidence that that's true.

01:06:00.070 --> 01:06:02.070
Now you're starting to
grasp at straws.

01:06:02.070 --> 01:06:04.070
So there's no evidence that
interview processes make any

01:06:04.070 --> 01:06:04.850
difference anywhere.

01:06:04.850 --> 01:06:06.680
But everybody does interviews
all the ways.

01:06:06.680 --> 01:06:08.950
Because we always think we're
kind of good judges of human

01:06:08.950 --> 01:06:11.020
nature or something.

01:06:11.020 --> 01:06:13.080
So interviews, it's very
hard to tell that

01:06:13.080 --> 01:06:14.070
they ever do anything.

01:06:14.070 --> 01:06:15.510
So here's my last thing.

01:06:15.510 --> 01:06:20.080
Self-esteem, you cannot watch
Oprah or Dr. Phil without some

01:06:20.080 --> 01:06:22.390
discussion of self-esteem
at some moment.

01:06:22.390 --> 01:06:23.440
And it sounds good
to everybody.

01:06:23.440 --> 01:06:25.366
I mean nobody would wish for you
as a parent or friend for

01:06:25.366 --> 01:06:26.950
you to have low self-esteem.

01:06:26.950 --> 01:06:29.540
And in fact, higher self-esteem
is correlated with

01:06:29.540 --> 01:06:31.580
higher initiative and
persistence, happiness and

01:06:31.580 --> 01:06:34.240
emotional resilience, and also,
unfortunately, with

01:06:34.240 --> 01:06:35.860
people who are narcissistic
and bullies.

01:06:39.300 --> 01:06:41.550
And how they measure it, just so
you know, because this is a

01:06:41.550 --> 01:06:44.500
problem, too, how do
you measure it?

01:06:44.500 --> 01:06:45.320
There's several scales.

01:06:45.320 --> 01:06:47.910
But the most widely used scale
is this Rosenberg scale.

01:06:47.910 --> 01:06:49.330
So you have that, too,
if you want to

01:06:49.330 --> 01:06:51.530
try it out on yourself.

01:06:51.530 --> 01:06:55.290
Self-report, and when they
reviewed 15,000 studies some

01:06:55.290 --> 01:06:57.920
years ago, they could find
no evidence that higher

01:06:57.920 --> 01:07:00.340
self-esteem leads to
better things.

01:07:00.340 --> 01:07:03.430
It all seemed the other way
around that doing better at

01:07:03.430 --> 01:07:05.920
things led to higher
self-esteem.

01:07:05.920 --> 01:07:07.660
They could never find
that pushing your

01:07:07.660 --> 01:07:08.320
self-esteem up doesn't.

01:07:08.320 --> 01:07:11.760
Having said that, I can tell you
as a parent of two young

01:07:11.760 --> 01:07:14.093
kids or if you have friends and
you care about them and

01:07:14.093 --> 01:07:16.020
you know this, we like to praise
people to build up

01:07:16.020 --> 01:07:16.980
their self-esteem.

01:07:16.980 --> 01:07:18.280
We tell you you're awesome.

01:07:18.280 --> 01:07:19.220
Someday you'll go to MIT.

01:07:19.220 --> 01:07:20.230
I know you will.

01:07:20.230 --> 01:07:21.170
You're a wonderful person.

01:07:21.170 --> 01:07:21.870
And you're smart.

01:07:21.870 --> 01:07:23.370
And you're beautiful.

01:07:23.370 --> 01:07:26.430
Parents want their children and
teachers, too, to grow up

01:07:26.430 --> 01:07:29.610
and thrive and build up
that self-esteem.

01:07:29.610 --> 01:07:32.070
And the easiest way to do that
is praise, right, just telling

01:07:32.070 --> 01:07:35.410
your kid how awesome he or she
is or your younger sibling how

01:07:35.410 --> 01:07:36.600
awesome her or she is.

01:07:36.600 --> 01:07:38.180
Get their self-esteem up.

01:07:38.180 --> 01:07:39.570
So the last thing I'm going to
tell you and then we'll be

01:07:39.570 --> 01:07:42.030
done in about three minutes is
work from Carol Dweck that

01:07:42.030 --> 01:07:45.850
shows you how dangerous it is
and counterproductive it is to

01:07:45.850 --> 01:07:51.400
have praise where you
don't think through

01:07:51.400 --> 01:07:52.590
its relation to people.

01:07:52.590 --> 01:07:55.540
And in one sense we'll talk
about, are you going to

01:07:55.540 --> 01:07:57.980
succeed in life by your
effort or your talent?

01:07:57.980 --> 01:07:59.590
What's a bigger question
than that?

01:07:59.590 --> 01:08:01.520
Wherever you get to in your
life, it's going to be based

01:08:01.520 --> 01:08:03.400
on your effort or your
talent or both.

01:08:03.400 --> 01:08:04.930
I'll just have a sentence
about that now.

01:08:04.930 --> 01:08:07.120
So here's the experiments she
did with fifth graders.

01:08:07.120 --> 01:08:09.460
She had them perform
a pretty hard task.

01:08:09.460 --> 01:08:12.530
And afterwards, randomly, they
were either praised for their

01:08:12.530 --> 01:08:12.825
intelligence.

01:08:12.825 --> 01:08:15.710
So a person said to
them, you, fifth

01:08:15.710 --> 01:08:17.540
grader, you are so smart.

01:08:17.540 --> 01:08:20.310
I can't believe how great you
did on that, fifth grader.

01:08:20.310 --> 01:08:22.100
Or they were praised for
their hard work.

01:08:22.100 --> 01:08:24.260
This shows a lot of hard
work, different kids.

01:08:24.260 --> 01:08:29.380
And some kids got no praise
at all in this experiment.

01:08:29.380 --> 01:08:33.550
Then they get a task that's
even a little bit harder.

01:08:33.550 --> 01:08:35.970
How does the different kind of
praise influence things?

01:08:35.970 --> 01:08:37.470
And here was the finding.

01:08:37.470 --> 01:08:41.060
If you were praised for your
intelligence, you did worse on

01:08:41.060 --> 01:08:41.930
the second test.

01:08:41.930 --> 01:08:44.310
If you were praised for your
hard work, you did better.

01:08:44.310 --> 01:08:47.370
If nobody said anything, your
performance didn't change.

01:08:47.370 --> 01:08:48.410
And the idea is this.

01:08:48.410 --> 01:08:50.210
You understand, praised for
your intelligence, you did

01:08:50.210 --> 01:08:51.649
worse on a hard task.

01:08:51.649 --> 01:08:53.290
Praised for your effort,
you did better.

01:08:53.290 --> 01:08:56.810
And here's the idea that, if
we praise people for their

01:08:56.810 --> 01:08:59.500
intelligence to build up their
self-esteem, they start to

01:08:59.500 --> 01:09:02.850
care more about how their
performance reflects on them

01:09:02.850 --> 01:09:04.840
than the performance itself.

01:09:04.840 --> 01:09:07.459
Because you're trying
to prove that you're

01:09:07.459 --> 01:09:10.200
an intelligent person.

01:09:10.200 --> 01:09:12.010
The students who get that
kind of praise for their

01:09:12.010 --> 01:09:15.069
intelligence, they persist
less in a difficult task.

01:09:15.069 --> 01:09:17.210
They say they don't
enjoy challenges.

01:09:17.210 --> 01:09:18.090
Why?

01:09:18.090 --> 01:09:19.779
They just want to ace everything
to keep proving

01:09:19.779 --> 01:09:22.200
they're smart.

01:09:22.200 --> 01:09:24.899
The kids who got praised for
effort, they're kind of like,

01:09:24.899 --> 01:09:26.029
OK, I'm going to make
some mistakes.

01:09:26.029 --> 01:09:26.960
But I'm just going
to keep going.

01:09:26.960 --> 01:09:29.069
Because with effort I can
do things sometimes.

01:09:29.069 --> 01:09:31.140
And it turns out that it makes
a remarkable thing.

01:09:31.140 --> 01:09:33.390
And so Dweck, and we'll come
back to this, talks about you

01:09:33.390 --> 01:09:37.600
can imbue your intelligence as
a trait, I have only so much,

01:09:37.600 --> 01:09:41.109
or as a growth, the harder I
work, the smarter I get.

01:09:41.109 --> 01:09:43.630
But I have to do the hard
work to get there.

01:09:43.630 --> 01:09:48.090
And we live in a society that
often goes by fixed traits.

01:09:48.090 --> 01:09:51.810
American Idol, the harder the
work, the better you sing or

01:09:51.810 --> 01:09:54.710
who has the talent
is discovered?

01:09:54.710 --> 01:09:57.890
Who has the talent is
discovered, right?

01:09:57.890 --> 01:09:59.900
Because the idea is
you have a certain

01:09:59.900 --> 01:10:01.000
amount of musical talent.

01:10:01.000 --> 01:10:01.960
And now the judges show.

01:10:01.960 --> 01:10:03.030
And you break into the world.

01:10:03.030 --> 01:10:05.590
And you're a famous
singer, right?

01:10:05.590 --> 01:10:08.410
So ask yourself this.

01:10:08.410 --> 01:10:11.600
When you are good at what you
do, is it because something in

01:10:11.600 --> 01:10:14.410
your genes and environment made
you good at it or is it

01:10:14.410 --> 01:10:16.410
because you try really hard?

01:10:16.410 --> 01:10:19.200
So Malcolm Gladwell has this
statement that's floating

01:10:19.200 --> 01:10:21.550
around, gets a lot of attention,
that anybody can

01:10:21.550 --> 01:10:23.280
become great at anything
if they work on

01:10:23.280 --> 01:10:27.020
it for 10,000 hours.

01:10:27.020 --> 01:10:29.990
So how much of your success in
the past, currently, and in

01:10:29.990 --> 01:10:32.960
the future is going be
based on your effort?

01:10:32.960 --> 01:10:35.960
And how much is it going to
be based on your talents?

01:10:35.960 --> 01:10:37.020
And how would we know that?

01:10:37.020 --> 01:10:40.172
And we're a very talent-oriented
society.

01:10:40.172 --> 01:10:43.180
And it seems like, the more we
encourage effort, maybe the

01:10:43.180 --> 01:10:44.510
more people might flourish.

01:10:44.510 --> 01:10:47.110
So we talked about how
psychology and science,

01:10:47.110 --> 01:10:50.170
experiments, brief history of
psychology experimentation,

01:10:50.170 --> 01:10:51.660
some issues in experimentation,
and some

01:10:51.660 --> 01:10:54.340
psychological topics, and some
practical information for

01:10:54.340 --> 01:10:56.890
being generous and kind and
winning friends rapidly.

